.TH DUMPEXE 1 "February 2026" "RetroCodeMess" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
dumpexe \- MS-DOS MZ EXE header analyzer, disassembler, and simulator
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dumpexe
.RB [ \-h | \-\-help ]
.br
.B dumpexe
.RB [ \-v | \-\-version ]
.br
.B dumpexe
.RB [ options ]
.I exe_file
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dumpexe
is a comprehensive utility for analyzing MS-DOS MZ format executable files. It provides TDUMP-style output with multiple analysis modes:
.IP \(bu 2
Static header analysis with detailed field information
.IP \(bu 2
Relocation table display with padding analysis
.IP \(bu 2
Hex+ASCII dumps with zero-compression (like hexdump -C)
.IP \(bu 2
x86-16 disassembly using Capstone (static code analysis)
.IP \(bu 2
DOS load simulation with register tracking (dynamic execution trace)

.SH OPTIONS
.SS General Options
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display usage information and exit. Also shown when no arguments are provided.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Display version information and exit.

.SS Display Sections
If no section options are given, only the static EXE header information is displayed.
Multiple options can be combined.

.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-relocation
Show relocation table with all entries, including header padding before and after the table.
The relocation table contains segment fixup locations that DOS applies when loading the program.
.TP
.BR \-x ", " \-\-hexdump
Show complete hex+ASCII dump from entry point to end of file.
Uses canonical hexdump -C format with zero-compression (repeated lines shown as *).
Useful for examining code, data, and embedded resources.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-disassemble
Show x86-16 disassembly from entry point to end of file using Capstone.
This is
.B static analysis
\- shows all instructions without execution.
Requires Capstone library support at build time.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Show all sections in order: static info, relocation table, hexdump, and disassembly.
Provides complete analysis of the executable.

.SS Simulation Options
.TP
.B \-\-simulate
Enable DOS load simulation mode. This performs
.B dynamic analysis
by simulating how DOS loads and starts the program. Shows:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Initial CPU register state (CS, IP, SS, SP, DS, ES, FLAGS, etc.)
.IP \(bu 2
Relocation fixups applied to the image
.IP \(bu 2
Register tracing - simple instruction emulation showing register changes
.RE
.TP
.BI \-\-base= XXXX
Set the load base segment for simulation (hexadecimal value, default: 1000h).
This is the segment address where DOS loads the program after the PSP (Program Segment Prefix).
Common values: 1000, 2000, etc.

.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
.SS Static Header Information
Always displayed first. Shows comprehensive EXE header analysis in TDUMP style:
.IP \(bu 2
DOS File Size, Load Image Size
.IP \(bu 2
Relocation Table entry count and address
.IP \(bu 2
Header Size, Memory Requirements
.IP \(bu 2
Entry Point locations (file offset and image offset)
.IP \(bu 2
Initial register values (SS:SP, CS:IP)

.SS Relocation Table (-r)
Formatted table showing each relocation entry with:
.IP \(bu 2
Entry number
.IP \(bu 2
Segment:Offset pair
.IP \(bu 2
File location in hex
.IP \(bu 2
Linear offset within image
.PP
Also shows any padding between header and relocation table, and between table and image.

.SS Hex+ASCII Dump (-x)
Complete dump from entry point to EOF in canonical hexdump -C format:
.IP \(bu 2
8-digit hex addresses (lowercase)
.IP \(bu 2
16 bytes per line with space after 8th byte
.IP \(bu 2
ASCII panel with | delimiters
.IP \(bu 2
Zero-compression: repeated identical lines shown as single * (saves enormous space)
.PP
Example:
.nf
00000420  1e b8 00 00 50 06 2e a1  00 00 8e c0 8e d8 58 a3  |....P.........X.|
00000430  00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00  00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00  |................|
*
00000450  ff ff ff ff 21 00 2a 00  33 00 44 00 55 00 66 00  |....!.*.3.D.U.f.|
.fi

.SS Disassembly (-d)
.B Static code analysis
using Capstone x86-16 disassembler. Shows:
.IP \(bu 2
File offset for each instruction
.IP \(bu 2
Raw instruction bytes
.IP \(bu 2
Mnemonic and operands
.PP
This is pure disassembly without execution context - useful for understanding program structure, finding functions, analyzing algorithms.

.SS Simulation (--simulate)
.B Dynamic execution trace
that simulates DOS loading and program startup:

.B Initial Register State:
.RS
Shows all CPU registers initialized as DOS would set them:
.IP \(bu 2
CS:IP = entry point with load base applied
.IP \(bu 2
SS:SP = stack pointer with load base applied
.IP \(bu 2
DS, ES = load base (typical DOS behavior)
.IP \(bu 2
AX, BX, CX, DX, SI, DI, BP = 0
.IP \(bu 2
FLAGS = 0002h (bit 1 always set on 8086)
.RE

.B Relocation Fixups:
.RS
Shows each segment value being adjusted:
.IP \(bu 2
Original segment value from file
.IP \(bu 2
Relocated value (original + load base)
.IP \(bu 2
Demonstrates how DOS patches segment references
.RE

.B Register Tracing (with Capstone):
.RS
Best-effort emulation of first ~20 instructions showing register changes:
.IP \(bu 2
.B xor ax,ax
/ 
.B xor bx,bx
/ 
.B xor cx,cx
/ 
.B xor dx,dx
\- zeroes specific register
.IP \(bu 2
.B push
/ 
.B pop
\- shows SP changes
.IP \(bu 2
.B int XX
\- notes DOS/BIOS interrupts

Not a full emulator - focuses on common register operations for quick insight into program initialization.
Only specific instruction patterns are recognized.
.RE

.SH STATIC vs DYNAMIC ANALYSIS
.B dumpexe
provides both analysis modes:

.B Static Analysis (-d):
.RS
Disassembles all code without execution. Shows complete instruction stream. Good for:
.IP \(bu 2
Understanding program structure
.IP \(bu 2
Finding all code paths
.IP \(bu 2
Analyzing algorithms
.IP \(bu 2
Searching for specific instruction patterns
.RE

.B Dynamic Analysis (--simulate):
.RS
Simulates execution from entry point. Shows register state changes. Good for:
.IP \(bu 2
Understanding program initialization
.IP \(bu 2
Seeing actual register values during startup
.IP \(bu 2
Verifying relocation correctness
.IP \(bu 2
Quick "what does it do first" analysis
.RE

.B Combined (-d --simulate):
.RS
Shows both full disassembly and dynamic trace - complete picture of the executable.
.RE

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Error (invalid file, bad arguments, corrupted header)

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B dumpexe program.exe
Show only static header information
.TP
.B dumpexe -r program.exe
Show header and relocation table
.TP
.B dumpexe -x game.exe
Show header and complete hex dump
.TP
.B dumpexe -d game.exe
Show header and full disassembly (static analysis)
.TP
.B dumpexe --simulate game.exe
Show header and DOS load simulation (dynamic analysis)
.TP
.B dumpexe -a program.exe
Show everything: relocations, hexdump, disassembly
.TP
.B dumpexe -d --simulate --base=2000 game.exe
Disassemble and simulate loading at segment 2000h
.TP
.B dumpexe -x program.exe | less
Page through hexdump output

.SH CAPSTONE SUPPORT
.B dumpexe
can be built with or without Capstone disassembly support:

.B With Capstone:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Full x86-16 disassembly available (-d flag)
.IP \(bu 2
Register tracing in simulation mode
.IP \(bu 2
Build: g++ -std=c++17 -o dumpexe dumpexe.cpp -lcapstone
.RE

.B Without Capstone:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
All other features work normally
.IP \(bu 2
-d and -a flags warn about missing support
.IP \(bu 2
Build: g++ -std=c++17 -o dumpexe dumpexe.cpp
.IP \(bu 2
Help text indicates Capstone not available
.RE

To add Capstone support: install libcapstone-dev package and rebuild.

.SH FILES
.TP
.B dumpexe.h
Header file containing all structures, register definitions, and utility functions
.TP
.B dumpexe.cpp
Main implementation file

.SH TECHNICAL DETAILS
.SS MZ EXE Format
.IP \(bu 2
Signature: 'MZ' (0x5A4D little-endian)
.IP \(bu 2
28-byte minimum header
.IP \(bu 2
Header sizes in paragraphs (16-byte units)
.IP \(bu 2
File size: ((num_blocks-1) × 512) + final_len
.IP \(bu 2
Entry point: header_size + (CS × 16) + IP

.SS Register State Representation
Uses packed unions and bitfields for authentic x86 register access:
.IP \(bu 2
AX/BX/CX/DX with hi/lo byte access (AH/AL, etc.)
.IP \(bu 2
Segment registers: CS, DS, ES, SS
.IP \(bu 2
Pointers: IP, SP, BP, SI, DI
.IP \(bu 2
FLAGS with individual bit access (CF, ZF, SF, OF, etc.)

.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
Read-only analysis - never modifies files
.IP \(bu 2
Works cross-platform (analyze DOS EXEs on Linux/Unix)
.IP \(bu 2
Zero-compression in hex dumps saves space for AI context windows
.IP \(bu 2
Hex values displayed lowercase (canonical format)
.IP \(bu 2
Simulation is best-effort, not cycle-accurate emulation

